{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"87060395-f463-4c1c-a4f6-7e1a3319ee61","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic. However, here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check macOS's built-in crash reports** — look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for system-wide). macOS automatically generates `.ips` / `.crash` files on process crashes.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** via:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **If `/cores` is missing or empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps and the directory exists:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For .NET-specific analysis**, load the SOS debugging extension in `lldb` via `dotnet-sos install`, then use `plugin load` in lldb to get managed stack traces.\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` by design — they rely on OS-native crash reporting. The macOS diagnostic reports and core dumps are the primary recovery paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3da6c143-bba9-4053-ba48-85d2b998d063","outputTokens":339,"requestId":"AC02:12E269:13EFD37:1664D87:6A0671B0"},"id":"1c75ac7c-db57-44c3-bd08-cf4c2c331797","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:07:06.658Z","parentId":"226804bd-e8c7-4c3a-ada1-6632fc211ab6"}
